      { id: 'C', text: 'C. 1. Specify sampled Shapley as the explanation method with a path count of 50. 2. Deploy the model to Vertex AI Endpoints. Create a Model Monitoring job using training-serving skew as the monitoring objective. Create a Model Monitoring job using training-serving skew as the monitoring objective.' },
      { id: 'D', text: 'D. 1. Specify Integrated Gradients as the explanation method with a path count of 50. 2. Deploy the model to Vertex AI Endpoints. 3.Create a Model Monitoring job using training-serving skew as the monitoring objective. Explanation: Overall explanation Incorrect Answers: Option B specifies Integrated Gradients as the explanation method with a path count of 5. This method is typically more suited to differentiable models like neural networks and may not be optimal for XGBoost. It also focuses on prediction drift for monitoring, which is useful, but the mismatch in the explanation method makes this option less ideal for a tree-based model like XGBoost. Option C also uses Sampled Shapley, which is a good fit for XGBoost, but with a higher path count of 50. This offers more accurate explanations but at the cost of increased latency. The monitoring objective here is training-serving skew, which tracks discrepancies between training and serving data distributions. While this is important, it does not directly address changes in feature attributions over time. Option D opts for Integrated Gradients with a path count of 50, which increases accuracy at the expense of higher latency. This explanation method is not the best fit for XGBoost. Like Option C, it uses training-serving skew as the monitoring objective, focusing on alignment between training and serving environments but not specifically on changes in the data or model behavior over time. Correct Answer Option A involves using Sampled Shapley as the explanation method with a low path count of 5, which is appropriate for an XGBoost model as it effectively captures feature contributions in tree-based models. This option aims to minimize latency in online predictions. The monitoring objective is prediction drift, which is essential for detecting changes in prediction behavior over time, making it a well-rounded choice for monitoring realworld applicability and model robustness. Reference: https://cloud.google.com/vertex-ai/docs/explainable-ai/overview' }
